 more contracts and generate more income. Sinc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e leaving BECT I have undertaken some consultancy work for the Community Transport Association</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. I am a parish councillor </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and an elected Parish </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ember on the Peak District National Park Authority. I also write walking guidebooks and run a website promoting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cycling in the Peak District. The following submission is from mysel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f as an individual and not on behalf of any organisation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local authorities need to be more creative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">flexible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in coordinating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and promoting </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rural bus transport, looking </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to mix and match approaches</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eg timetabled vs demand responsive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, as well as variations that are suited to particular localities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Opportunities must be sought to integrate rural bus services with other transport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">movements</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for rural communities, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eg for the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">purposes of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> health, shopping and education, thus driving down costs and maximising revenue for operators.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Rural bus services need to be marketed more imaginatively so that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there is a better understanding of the network and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">encouragement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to use local servi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ces. In popular visitor areas tourists and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recreational users </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">must also be targeted so that they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">become part of the passenger base and help ensure viability of routes. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local people need to be part of the solution and play an active role in determining lo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cal need and seeking workable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ways forward</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, eg through community planning and localism. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There must be more discussion and analysis of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ransport and the daily movements of residents in rural areas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">if lasting solutions are to be found. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Community Transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has real potential to deliver </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">effective local bus services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, but the sector needs commissioners to be more enlightened</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and give Community Transport greater parity with commercial operators when procuring services. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Ingrained attitudes towards Community Tran</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sport need to change. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For their part, Community Transport organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> need targeted business development help</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to foster a more enterprising attitude and allow their social enterprises to grow sustainably.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Bus transport in rural areas</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">To what </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">extent are the needs of different groups of passengers taken into account in determining the provision of public transport to isolated communities?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">From my experience of rural Derbyshire and in particular the villages of the Peak District (not the valley </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">arteries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> connecting the towns), publicly subsidised service buses are routinely running round </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">empty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or near empty </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the middle of the day. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is even the case at weekends, when visitors and recreational users should be using them. It is a ludicrous situ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ation that points to a funda</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mental lack of understanding of their customers’ needs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in terms of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">actually want to go and when</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. It also suggests</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a lack of political will to explore new and imaginative solutions for rural public transport delivery.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The problem is being compounded by the local authority (as elsewhere) cutting back services, in particular those deemed fringe or unprofitable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that hit the vulnerable users even harder. In my own village the late evening bus back from Bakewell has been a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">xed so that the teenagers now have to rely on lifts or taxis and have stopped using the bus for even the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">earlier </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">outward journey. We are in danger of developing a rural generation for whom bus transport is an altogether alien concept!</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Quite apart from pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vision, the marketing and promotion of rural bus services is often poor or lacklustre, especially towards a younger age group. There is little or no regard for the customer profile and what publicity there is tends to be formulaic and unimaginative.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The po</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rtrayal of b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">us transport in rural areas is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">staid and comes across as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the preserve of the elderly or poor, which is wholly wrong.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What are the main challenges associated with funding transport services in isolated communities? How can these services be ma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">de more affordable?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There has to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">acceptance that delivering bus transport for remote rural communities is not and never will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as cost effective as it is in urban areas, or even clusters of market towns; but that inhabitants of rural communities sh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ould not be penalised for this. Indeed, it is arguable that people from deep rural areas are more in need of effective and efficient transport solutions, as transport poverty can lead to real </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and not just relative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">social isolation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">More imaginative approa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ches to rural bus transport have to be trialled that seek to integrate services and so reduce unit costs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (see below)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">; encourage local providers like </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ommunity </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ransport operators to play a more proactive role; and explore new ways of working like demand </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">responsive minibuses instead of old and inflexible 50-seater coaches (see below).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In my own area (the Derbyshire Peak District) any subsidised bus service deemed visitor-orient</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed is being cut – but this is an entirely </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">backward-looking </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">step</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">! In a popular N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ational Park visitors should be using buses to get around and reach the remote villages and walks that they are seeking</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, just</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as long as they </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> get to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the location, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the timetable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> meets their needs and the service is reliable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. And if they were doing this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in sufficient number</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> routes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> wouldn’t need so much subsidy and the services could </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in turn </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be more affordable to local people. Local tourism businesses and attractions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">might then</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> sponsor or advertise on the buses more and thus </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">help drive down costs furt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">her.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Rural buses must be marketed to all users so that all users benefit.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How do Government and local authorities identify demand for passenger transport in isolated communities?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">One of the obvious first steps is to understand the rural communities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">themselves –</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> where people</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> want to go, when, how, etc? Parish Councils and community groups can help with accessibility audits to plot work/shopping/health/leisure transport movements of local residents, so that gaps and opportunities can be identified, pilot service ideas can be w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">orked up and even more creative solutions such as local travel clubs explored.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> In this way transport should be made a key plank of emerging Neighbourhood Plans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> so that local communities take more ownership of transport matters and themselves identify possi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ble solutions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Transport operators, social enterprises, local authorities – whoever! – should work hand in hand with these local representatives to explore new delivery models that connect village to village, village to town, etc, and seek to integrate as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> many types of journey as possible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. For example, a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">shopping</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">service from a cluster of villages to a town that is also timed to coincide with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">health centre’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> opening hours; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">an early morning work/training </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that goes on to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">do </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> run</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">; an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evening </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ervice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">from villages </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to an adult education centre </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in a nearby town </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that also visits the local cinema/skate park, etc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The aim is to reduce unit costs, create a single market and optimise the operator’s resources. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hink bold, think imaginatively! Instead </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of rigid timetabled services that don’t necessarily correspond with people’s desired journey times and patterns, perhaps a demand responsive approach </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">might</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> work best</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in some rural locations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">? Moorlands Connect </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bus </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">service (run by Ashbourne Community Transpo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rt) is one such example, combining shopping services and even school runs for remote villages on the Staffordshire Moorlands with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">income</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from visiting walkers and cyclists</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, since </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> buses have bike racks attached</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">www.staffordshire.gov.uk/transport/public</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">transport/buses/connect/</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">MoorlandsConnect.aspx</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">emand responsive transport (DRT) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">concept </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">can take some understand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, but essentially only sending a vehicle where it’s needed and when makes perfect sense</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the rural context where passenger patterns can alter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (and if </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the bus i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s idle for too long there’s something wrong with its coverage, promotion or pricing). </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> DRT can also operate very well on a semi-flexible </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or semi-timetabled </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">basis, so that the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> drive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r can deviate from a set route to collect passengers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t’s ideal for a rural bus route that connects a string of villages and hamlets </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fluctuating passenger numbers) to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a town.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Although DRT can be expensive to set up, if it’s designed so that it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> incorporates other services (eg </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">daily run to a rural primary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">school, a regular adult social care run, a weekly luncheon club run for elderly villagers, etc) and also marketed to other users like visitors, then it can be cost effective and viable for rur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">al situations. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.11</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There needs to be more joined-up thinking from transport authorities and operators, so that, for instance, bus routes from remoter rural locations </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">clearly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">act as feeders to main bus routes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">wider rural </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> network is presented more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">logically and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">coherently. As an example, see the Interconnect and Call Connect rur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">al bus networks in Lincolnshire that all feed into each other and are presented as such</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (www.lincsinterconnect.com).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How effectively do Community Transport services address</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> the needs of passengers in isolated communities? How could Community Transport be improved?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.12</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Community </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ransport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">operators (CTOs) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the potential to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">deliver effective local solutions for rural people, not least because of their social commitment, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">energ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y and enthusiasm, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local knowledge, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as well as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">capacity and expertise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> deal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with elderly a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd disabled passengers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In fact, there are numerous examples where CTOs are already a lifeline for people with access issues from remote or hard-to-reach rural co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mmunities. Furthermore</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, many </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">CTOs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are already and successfully </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">running contracted services for local authorities, NHS trusts, and so on. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.13</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oo many service commissioners still appear to regard CTOs as amateurish and voluntary, fringe transport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> older people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cheap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Many l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ocal authorities in particular need to start embracing Community Transport as part of the solution for delivering rural public transport in deep rural areas and work with them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on a more level playing field, rather than tur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ning to the commercial operators first every time. Procurement processes still tend to be geared up towards the big operators and it can be a frustrating and difficult nut for CTOs to crack.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hope</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that the Public Services (Social Value) Act may gradua</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lly begin to change procurement attitudes – but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> doesn’t seem to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">much evidence of this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> yet.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Perceptions of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Community Transport must change if CTOs are to play a more fulfilling role.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.14</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With some notable exceptions, CTOs themselves are mostly small social enterprises and organisations that are at various stages of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">relatively</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> early </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">growth. Some will probably choose to stay small and local, but those others that seek to grow need more assis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tance in terms of business advice and development, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">so that they can </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">build </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">capacity and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">resilience, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">improve their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">financial know-how and so on. (This is evidenced with the recent sad demise of Little Red Bus and Nene &amp; Ouse Community Transport.)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.15</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Without lo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sing sight of their social goals, these CTOs also need to be encouraged to think more enterprisingly and so overcome </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">internal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cultural barriers as well as physical </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">challenges</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> like cash flow, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">regulations, contract law, accreditation, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">etc. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There’s a need for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> training for board members/trustees and not just key staff in terms of strategic development and risk taking, for example. Although most CTOs may be young and relatively small, those that I have come across certainly have the drive and commitment to deliv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">er effective transport solutions for rural communities – they just need the right </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">social enterprise </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tools and opportunities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.16</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In most instances CTOs will simply be part of the rural transport mix and transport authorities and service commissioners must </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">understand this a little better, recognising both the strengths and limitations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of Community Transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. While the big commercial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">operators will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> no doubt carry on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> cover</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the main through routes, busy school runs, etc, CTOs are ideally placed to supply the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> feeder services, link the remoter and hard to reach villages, not least because of the composition of their fleets (accessible small minibuses) and expert knowledge </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in terms o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f both local geography and running demand responsive services. Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ere are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> already</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">able examples</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in some locations, but elsewhere </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">national operators are still paid to trundle </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">empty service buses </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">around villages</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">based on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> inflexible timetables.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.17</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Despite </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the shortcomings and barriers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, where Community Transport is well run </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">– </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and in particular works with a progressive local authority </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to address </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">particular </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">issue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">it is quite clear that it can deliver lasting results for rural communities. For instance, see bus routes operated by Third Sector Services and CCVS Trading</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the Co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tswolds, or the Suffolk Links DRT routes run by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Coastal Accessible Transport Services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">www.suffolkonboard.com/suffolk-links-demand-responsive-transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:left;"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>